04702nam a22007815i 9781442689466DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2016    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426894667 a10.3138/97814426894662doi  a(DE-B1597)465380  a(OCoLC)1002262812  a(OCoLC)1004872128  a(OCoLC)1011460430  a(OCoLC)1013955387  a(OCoLC)944176501  a(OCoLC)999372195  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPN5117 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a910.9163/271 aCavell, Janice, eauthor.10aTracing the Connected Narrative :bArctic Exploration in British Print Culture, 1818-1860 /cJanice Cavell. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tMaps -- tIntroduction -- t1. The End of an Epic, 1859-1860 -- t2. The Dreams of Romance, 1818 -1820 -- t3. The Threshold of a World Unknown, 1820-1821 -- t4. A Romance in Real Life, 1821-1824 -- t5. The Nelsons of Discovery -- t6. Their Tribute from the General Voice, 1823-1848 -- t7. The Knight-errantry of Our Day, 1848-1852 -- t8. The Duty of a People, 1852-1857 -- t9. A Sacred Sorrow, 1857-1860 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy the 1850s, journalists and readers alike perceived Britain's search for the Northwest Passage as an ongoing story in the literary sense. Because this 'story' appeared, like so many nineteenth-century novels, in a series of installments in periodicals and reviews, it gained an appeal similar to that of fiction. Tracing the Connected Narrative examines written representations of nineteenth-century British expeditions to the Canadian Arctic. It places Arctic narratives in the broader context of the print culture of their time, especially periodical literature, which played an important role in shaping the public's understanding of Arctic exploration.Janice Cavell uncovers similarities between the presentation of exploration reports in periodicals and the serialized fiction that, she argues, predisposed readers to take an interest in the prolonged quest for the Northwest Passage. Cavell examines the same parallel in relation to the famous disappearance and subsequent search for the Franklin expedition. After the fate of Sir John Franklin had finally been revealed, the Illustrated London News printed a list of earlier articles on the missing expedition, suggesting that the public might wish to re-read them in order to 'trace the connected narrative' of this chapter in the Arctic story. Through extensive research and reference to new archival material, Cavell undertakes this task and, in the process, recaptures and examines the experience of nineteenth-century readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442689466423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442689466.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG